		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Patrick Leigh Fermor</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<p><b>Sir Patrick 'Paddy' Michael Leigh Fermor</b> <a href="/wiki/Distinguished_Service_Order" title="Distinguished Service Order">DSO</a> <a href="/wiki/Order_of_the_British_Empire" title="Order of the British Empire">OBE</a> (born <span class="mw-formatted-date" title="1915-02-11"><a href="/wiki/February_11" title="February 11">11 February</a> <a href="/wiki/1915" title="1915">1915</a></span>, <a href="/wiki/London" title="London">London</a>) is a <a href="/wiki/United_Kingdom" title="United Kingdom">British</a> author, scholar and soldier, who played a prominent role behind the lines in the <a href="/wiki/Battle_of_Crete" title="Battle of Crete">Battle of Crete</a> during <a href="/wiki/World_War_II" title="World War II">World War II</a>. He is famous for his <a href="/wiki/Travel_literature" title="Travel literature">travel writing</a> and is widely regarded as "Britain's greatest living travel writer". <sup id="cite_ref-books.guardian.co.uk_0-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-books.guardian.co.uk-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
